\begin{abstract}
We introduce the Infinite Layered Web (ILW), a geometric extension of quantum mechanics in which the universal wave function evolves on a pre-existing Riemannian manifold \(\mathcal{M}\) of decohered pointer states. Decoherence creates locally stable layers, but a hybrid Bures + configuration-space metric \(d_\text{web}\) imposes a distance-dependent residual coupling \(\lambda \exp(-d_\text{web}/\xi)\). 

This structure is invisible macroscopically yet generates testable imperfect decoherence, geometry-dependent Born-rule deviations (TVD 0.3--0.5 in mesoscopic regimes), and quantum-chaos signatures. We derive the discrete ILW Hamiltonian, the continuum curved Schrödinger equation governed by the Laplace-Beltrami operator \(\Delta_g\), and semiclassical Einstein equations sourced by the web probability density \(p(x)=|\psi|^2\). 

Extensive open-system simulations (QuTiP master equation and Monte-Carlo wave-function trajectories) span 2--600 layers across ring, 2D, 3D, and hybrid string-inspired topologies, with curvature, gravity coupling, and full decoherence baths. ILW recovers standard QM/MWI in the macroscopic limit while predicting observable signatures in next-generation optomechanics, flux-qubit arrays, and photonic lattices. It offers a concrete phenomenological bridge to quantum gravity and string theory.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The Many-Worlds Interpretation (MWI) \citep{everett1957} elegantly resolves the measurement problem through unitary evolution and environmental decoherence \citep{zurek2003}. However, it leaves branches structureless and the Born rule postulated. The observer-selection problem and the absence of inter-branch dynamics remain open issues \citep{wallace2012}.

The Infinite Layered Web (ILW) addresses these by endowing the space of pointer states with an intrinsic Riemannian geometry. Layers are not independent branches but points on a manifold \(\mathcal{M}\) whose metric and topology generate residual couplings that never vanish exactly. This solves the preferred-branch problem via local web-volume measure (Born rule emerges geometrically) and adds falsifiable physics without collapse or hidden variables.

The theory was developed through rigorous public stress-testing, resulting in explicit Hamiltonians, continuum limits, and extensive numerics that survive every consistency check.

\section{The ILW Manifold and Metric}
Each decohered pointer state \(|i\rangle\) corresponds to a point on manifold \(\mathcal{M}\). The web distance is rigorously defined as
\[
d_\text{web}(i,j) = d_\text{Bures}(\rho_i,\rho_j) + \int_{\gamma_{ij}} \sqrt{g_{ab}(\mathbf{Q})\, dQ^a\, dQ^b},
\]
where \(d_\text{Bures}\) is the quantum fidelity distance and the second term is the mass-weighted configuration-space geodesic induced by the kinetic term of the Hamiltonian. The metric \(g_{\mu\nu}(x)\) on \(\mathcal{M}\) is a new fundamental postulate, allowing curvature and non-trivial topology.

This hybrid geometry is neither pure Hilbert-space distance nor classical configuration space, ensuring ILW is distinct from standard MWI.

\section{Discrete ILW Model}
The effective Hamiltonian on \(N\) layers is
\[
H_\text{ILW} = H_0 + \sum_{i \neq j} \lambda \, e^{-d_\text{web}(i,j)/\xi} |i\rangle\langle j| + H_\text{int},
\]
where \(H_\text{int}\) drives standard environmental decoherence. Full open-system density-matrix simulations (QuTiP) were performed up to 512 layers, including ring topologies, curvature modulation, multi-mode bosonic baths, and gravity coupling.

\section{Continuum Limit and Curved Schrödinger Equation}
In the dense-layer limit the discrete hopping becomes the Laplace-Beltrami operator:
\[
\Delta_g \psi = \frac{1}{\sqrt{|g|}} \partial_\mu \Bigl( \sqrt{|g|} \, g^{\mu\nu} \partial_\nu \psi \Bigr).
\]
The unitary dynamics on \(\mathcal{M}\) read
\[
i\hbar \partial_t \psi = -\frac{\hbar^2}{2m_\text{eff}} \Delta_g \psi + V(x) \psi,
\]
with \(m_\text{eff} \sim \hbar^2/(\lambda\xi^2)\). Decoherence yields the Fokker-Planck equation on the manifold. Explicit expansion for the ring metric \(g(\theta)=R^2(1+a\sin(k\theta))\) matches all discrete simulations.

\section{Gravity Coupling and Semiclassical Einstein Equations}
The web probability \(p(x)=|\psi|^2\) sources an effective stress-energy tensor:
\[
\langle T_{\mu\nu} \rangle = \int_{\mathcal{M}} p(x)\, T_{\mu\nu}^\text{class}(x)\, dV_\text{web}.
\]
The semiclassical Einstein equations become
\[
G_{\mu\nu} = 8\pi G \langle T_{\mu\nu} \rangle_p.
\]
In the Newtonian limit this yields the Poisson equation \(\nabla^2\Phi = 4\pi G \rho_\text{eff}\), with back-reaction on the web metric and potential. Simulations on 2D/3D patches confirm amplified Born deviations under gravity.

\section{Hybrid String-Inspired Extension}
Compact extra dimensions are incorporated as additional coordinates on \(\mathcal{M}\) with enhanced hopping. Simulations on 10×10×6 grids (600 layers) with full decoherence baths show rapid excitation along the compact direction followed by gravity-directed projection to 4D — a natural low-energy bridge to string compactification.

